ce:section.ce:para:
The voltammetric behavior of anthracene (AN) and naphthalene (NA) were studied using the cyclic voltammetric method in 0.1 M LiClO4. The bare GCE and C-dots-AgNPs modified GCE electrodes were inserted into a cell containing Ag/AgCl and Pt wire as reference and counter electrodes immersed in a 0.1 M LiClO4 in acetonitrile supporting electrolyte. No responses were observed in the absence of AN and NA in 0.1 M LiClO4 in acetonitrile. On the contrary, in the presence of 100 μM of AN and NA, the cyclic voltammogram of both bare GCE and C-dots-AgNPs/GCE showed two distinct oxidation peaks, one at 1.2 V and the other at 1.7 V corresponding to oxidation of AN and NA respectively. The oxidizing ability of C-dots-AgNPs/GCE was found to be high, as confirmed by the CVs showing sharp oxidation peaks for both AN and NA compared with that of bare electrode (Fig. 5A
                           ). The AN and NA were attracted by the carbon dots due to the pi-pi stacking interactions. As a result, AN and NA get closer to the electrode surface and get oxidized with a loss of one electron when the potential is applied between the working and the reference electrode. Moreover, the oxidation product of AN and NA yields a positively charged intermediate which is further attracted by the negatively charged carboxyl groups present at the edges of the carbon dots. Further, the water molecule gets attached to the electron-deficient carbon centre which further loses electrons and protons resulting in the formation of hydroxyl derivatives of AN and NA respectively. The existence of Π-Π stacking and the negatively charged functional groups in the carbon dots were the major reason for the sensing behavior of the modified electrode. As AgNPs have high surface area and excellent electron transfer ability, it transfers the electrons released during the oxidation of AN and NA to the electrode. When compared to AgNPs and carbon dots alone modified electrodes, the carbon dots-AgNPs modified electrode showed superior catalytic activity towards AN and NA. This is due to the synergic effects between the carbon dots and AgNPs (Scheme 1
                           ).
